cu500_pal | 1 | Neat, large, open thuluth, fully pointed and voweled, all in black ink.  Hamzah and sukun are sometimes accompanied by a red dot of later insertion.  For punctuation signs only the letters t (for waqf tamm), k (for waqf kafi), and h (for waqf hasan) are used.  They are in blue.  The following letters, written in red ink above the letters or words concerned, are used to ensure the correct pronunciation: gh (for idgham or assimilation), z (for izhar or vigorous and clear utterance), kh (for ikhfa&apos; or partial assimilation), and bgh (for idgham Basri to indicate assmiliation by the Basran school).  Variant readings are give in the margins with the variations in red and the ramz, or letter symbol for each reader, in black.  All of these signs are later additions to the text.
